[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_first_pass.md:5:> According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback most effectively regulates behavior change when paired with explicit goals, norms or targets that allow recipients to gauge their performance and direct their efforts accordingly (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996, 1998; Locke & Latham, 2019; Itzchakov & Latham, 2018; Chen, Latham, & Piccolo, 2020).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_first_pass.md:7:> Taken together, the original Schultz et al. (2007) findings and later reprise by Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018) underscore that descriptive feedback is most effective when it is accompanied by normative information about what behavior is desirable, a conclusion echoed in more recent applied feedback interventions in energy and household conservation domains (Andor, Gerster, & Peters, 2020; Henry, Ferraro, & Kontoleon, 2019; Mertens & Schultz, 2021).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_first_pass.md:15:> This logic implies a boundary condition on when descriptive feedback alone should motivate change. The classical feedback literature establishes that pairing feedback with an explicit goal can work because it supplies a standard against which past performance can be evaluated. However, an explicit goal should be less necessary when a strong implicit standard is already entrenched. Diversity-related selection decisions provide a clean test of this claim because anti-discrimination law, social and reputational pressures to avoid appearing prejudiced, and selectorsΓÇÖ personally held egalitarian self-image jointly sustain an entrenched implicit injunctive norm against prejudiced selection (Plant & Devine, 1998; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; ├ülvarez-Benjumea, 2023). When descriptive feedback reveals a discrepancy between that implicit standard and past behavior, we theorize that motivation to respond without prejudice will be activated even in the absence of a specific external goal.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_first_pass.md:23:> According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Locke & Latham, 2019; Schultz et al., 2007; Schultz, Nolan, & Cialdini, 2018).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_first_pass.md:31:> Our account also clarifies two forms of motivation through which descriptive feedback can change selection decisions. External motivation to control prejudice should be strongest when selection decisions are observable to colleagues, prospective candidates, supervisors, customers, employees, or outside stakeholders, and when evaluators face legal accountability or reputational costs for choices that appear exclusionary. In this sense, firmsΓÇÖ public DEI rhetoric is better understood as one downstream signal of broader legal, employee, customer, and reputational pressures, rather than the source of the implicit injunctive norm itself (Levi & Fried, 2024). Internal motivation to control prejudice, by contrast, reflects selectorsΓÇÖ personally held egalitarian beliefs and their desire to view themselves as non-prejudiced decision makers. This latter mechanism may be less sensitive to a given organizationΓÇÖs current DEI rhetoric, and it is the pathway most directly supported by Study 4, where feedback was delivered privately and internal motivation to respond without prejudice mediated subsequent selections. Study 4BΓÇÖs political-ideology null is consistent with this broader account, suggesting that external motivation to control prejudice and internal motivation to control prejudice may both operate across the political spectrum.
