[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_first_pass.md:75:Why this wording: These entries reproduce the response letterΓÇÖs reference list and use standard APA-style formatting. Devine & Ash (2022) should be cited in Introduction line 15 near the Ellis (2025) organizational-diversity sentence as a multidisciplinary review of diversity training.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:47:> We have modernized the references that anchor our theoretical framing in response to Reviewer 1's request for more contemporary citations. Both the Introduction and General Discussion now draw on more recent feedback, goalΓÇæsetting, and socialΓÇænorms work (e.g., Locke & Latham, 2019; Itzchakov & Latham, 2018; Chen, Latham, & Piccolo, 2020; Schultz, Nolan, & Cialdini, 2018; Devine & Ash, 2022; Andor, Gerster, & Peters, 2020; Henry, Ferraro, & Kontoleon, 2019; Mertens & Schultz, 2021), alongside the foundational citations we retain.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:51:> We have situated the paper in the current sociopolitical landscape around DEI, in response to Reviewer 2's concern that the prior version read as preΓÇæ2024. We now acknowledge the recent U.S. retreat from explicit DEI rhetoric while documenting three countervailing patterns that keep our central question relevant: (a) expanded international transparency requirements (Australia's Workplace Gender Equality Amendment Act 2023, the EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970, and the EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381); (b) continued U.S. public and stakeholder support for corporate DEI (e.g., the 2025 Bentley/Gallup survey reporting majority public support, and recent defeats of antiΓÇæDEI shareholder proposals at Costco, Apple, Levi's, John Deere, and Goldman Sachs); and (c) firmΓÇælevel rebranding of diversity work (toward "belonging," "inclusive culture," and related framings) rather than wholesale dismantling.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:75:> **RESPONSE:** We have addressed both of these. The Introduction and General Discussion now draw on more contemporary work in the feedback, goalΓÇæsetting, and socialΓÇænorms literatures (e.g., Locke & Latham, 2019; Itzchakov & Latham, 2018; Chen, Latham, & Piccolo, 2020; Schultz, Nolan, & Cialdini, 2018; Devine & Ash, 2022; Andor, Gerster, & Peters, 2020; Henry, Ferraro, & Kontoleon, 2019; Mertens & Schultz, 2021), alongside the foundational citations we retain (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al., 2007). We have also expanded the Introduction's theoretical framing (pp. XΓÇæX) to articulate why descriptive feedback alone can shift selection decisions about women and underrepresented minorities. Consistent with the broader logic of the feedback literature, feedback regulates behavior only when past performance can be evaluated against a standard; we now make explicit that this standard need not be supplied by an explicit goal when an implicit injunctive norm against prejudicial selection is already entrenched, as it is for the diversityΓÇærelated selection decisions we study. We address Reviewer 1's specific suggestions in detail below.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:79:> **RESPONSE:** We have addressed both points. The Introduction (pp. X) and General Discussion now situate the paper within the current sociopolitical landscape around DEI: we acknowledge the recent U.S. retreat from explicit DEI rhetoric while documenting three countervailing patterns that reinforce the contemporary relevance of our central question, namely expanded international transparency requirements (Australia's WGEA amendment 2023; the EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970; the EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381), continued U.S. public and stakeholder support for corporate DEI (Bentley/Gallup, 2025; defeated antiΓÇæDEI shareholder proposals at Costco, Apple, Levi's, John Deere, and Goldman Sachs), and firmΓÇælevel rebranding of diversity work toward "belonging" and "inclusive culture" framings rather than wholesale dismantling.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:81:> On the theoretical positioning, we now distinguish two pathways through which descriptive feedback shifts selection decisions: an *external* motivation to respond without prejudice, sustained by antiΓÇædiscrimination law, the observability of selection decisions, and broader reputational pressures that operate well beyond any one firm's stated DEI commitments (Levi & Fried, 2024); and an *internal* motivation to respond without prejudice, rooted in selectors' personally held egalitarian selfΓÇæimage, which should be relatively insensitive to organizational climate and is the pathway most directly supported by Study 4's privateΓÇæfeedback paradigm and mediation evidence. We expect our effect to generalize wherever selections are observable and selectors hold at least some egalitarian commitments, and to attenuate in fully private or anonymous selection contexts and in organizational settings that explicitly disavow egalitarian norms. We now flag organizational DEI climate as a scope condition and direction for future research in the General Discussion's *Future Directions and Limitations* section.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:120:We have updated the references Reviewer 1 flagged as dated. Our introduction now provides more contemporary citations (e.g., to Locke and Latham (2019), Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018), Andor, Gerster, and Peters (2020), Henry, Ferraro, and Kontoleon (2019), and Mertens and Schultz (2021)); the General Discussion does the same, incorporating more recent work alongside the foundational citations we retain (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al., 2007)
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:122:We have revised the Introduction (pp. X) and Discussion to acknowledge the shifting socio-political landscape around organizational commitments to DEI in the United States flagged by Reviewer 2. We situate our work within two parallel developments. In the U.S., explicit DEI rhetoric has retreated since 2024. In addition, international governments have moved in the opposite direction, passing laws that require firms to disclose or correct gender disparities in pay and leadership. Australia's Workplace Gender Equality Amendment (Closing the Gender Pay Gap) Act of 2023 mandates public disclosure of firm-level gender representation and pay gaps (Ressia, 2024). The EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970 requires transposition across member states by June 2026 (Mignano, 2024). The EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381 establishes a 40% gender minimum on listed-company boards. We argue that these shifts reinforce the contemporary value of our research even against an ever-changing sociopolitical backdrop, with a recent decline in support for corporate diversity policies specifically in the United States.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:123:We have provided a more tightly bounded theoretical discussion of the scope of our intervention, in line with Reviewer 2ΓÇÖs request. We agree that motivation to respond without prejudice is central to our account of increasing selections of women and racial minorities. However, we also discuss how the organizational climate around DEI is merely one part of the external motivation to respond without prejudice pathway that can influence individuals when it comes to promoting women and racial minorities. Specifically, the external motivation to control prejudice pathway also encompasses the fact that selection decisions are generally observable by colleagues, prospective candidates, and outside stakeholders, and the implicit norm against appearing prejudiced operates well beyond any one firmΓÇÖs stated commitments. While organizationsΓÇÖ explicit DEI commitments are themselves often responses to external stakeholder, legal, and political pressures rather than the source of internal organizational norms (Levi & Fried, 2024), a given firmΓÇÖs retreat from DEI rhetoric reflects shifting external pressure on the firm, not the disappearance of broader social pressure on individual selection decisions. We also now discuss how the internal motivation to respond without prejudice as well as selectorsΓÇÖ personally-held egalitarian beliefs may not be as malleable in the face of changes in organizational climate, and our existing evidence for why people respond to feedback about the race and gender of their past selectees (see Study 4) is, if anything, more readily explained by internal rather than external motives. In summary, we expect our effect to generalize wherever selections are observable and selectors hold at least some egalitarian commitments, and to be somewhat attenuated in fully private/anonymous selection decisions or in contexts that explicitly encourage discriminatory behavior.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:164:For the point about explicit goals being necessarily you cite some older stuff (e.g., Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al.,2007), any updated cites you can chuck in? Just makes it clearer how this is fitting in with contemporary literature in this area given that this is the first implication you discuss and the bigger one, IΓÇÖd like to see a bit more there.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:165:RESPONSE: Thank you for this helpful suggestion. We have updated our citations so we now cite Locke and Latham (2019) alongside the classic XX as well as Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018) alongside the classic XXX. These new citations reference contemporary updates to two foundational pieces we previously cited.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:167:RESPONSE: Thank you for pressing us on this point. We have refreshed the introductionΓÇÖs feedback and goals citations to draw on more recent work, including Locke and Latham (2019), Itzchakov and Latham (2018), Chen, Latham, and Piccolo (2020), Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018), and Devine and Ash (2022); and we have added applied work that the reviewerΓÇÖs prior comment first prompted us to incorporate (Andor, Gerster, & Peters, 2020; Henry, Ferraro, & Kontoleon, 2019; Mertens & Schultz, 2021).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:168:More importantly, we have also expanded the theoretical framing (pp. X-X) to discuss how the classical feedback literature establishes that pairing feedback with an explicit goal works, but consistent with the broader logic of this literature, feedback regulates behavior only when there is a standard against which past performance can be evaluated. Our argument is that descriptive feedback can also be effective in domains where a strong implicit standard is already entrenched, such that no explicit goal need be paired alongside it. More specifically, we discuss how feedback evoking the past treatment of women and racial minorities provides a clean test of this theory. We note that anti-discrimination law, social and reputational pressures to behave in ways that are not prejudicial, and selectorsΓÇÖ personally held egalitarian self-image jointly sustain an entrenched injunctive norm against prejudiced selection (Plant & Devine, 1998; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; ├ülvarez-Benjumea, 2023). When descriptive feedback reveals a discrepancy between this implicit standard and past behavior, we theorize that a motivation to respond without prejudice is activated even in the absence of a specific external goal.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_v3_review.log:178:The revised manuscript now more thoroughly discusses the fluctuating corporate posture toward DEI over the past five years: a period in which many U.S. organizations first rapidly adopted pro-DEI rhetoric and commitments, and then many of those same organizations have since scaled back on those commitments under new political, legal, and reputational pressures. At the same time, we also acknowledge three countervailing patterns that have occurred in parallel. First, internationally, regulatory demand for transparency around demographic representation is expanding. For example, AustraliaΓÇÖs Workplace Gender Equality Amendment (Closing the Gender Pay Gap) Act 2023 mandates public reporting of firm-level gender representation and pay-gap data (Ressia, 2024); the EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970 requires member-state transposition by June 2026 (Mignano, 2024); and the EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381 establishes a 40% representation objective for the underrepresented gender on listed-company boards. Second, within the U.S., public and stakeholder sentiment has shifted more slowly than corporate and legal rhetoric. For instance a 2025 Bentley/Gallup survey reports that 69% of U.S. adults believe businesses should promote DEI (Bentley/Gallup, 2025), and anti-DEI shareholder proposals have failed at numerous prominent organizations, including Costco, Apple, LeviΓÇÖs, John Deere, Goldman Sachs, and others (CBS, 2025; Marketplace, 2025). Third, within corporations, many firms appear to have rebranded or reframed diversity-related work rather than dismantling it entirely. For example, Constellation Brands now uses ΓÇ£Inclusive Culture Team,ΓÇ¥ KohlΓÇÖs has shifted to ΓÇ£Chief Inclusion and Belonging Officer,ΓÇ¥ and Nationwide and UPS have migrated toward ΓÇ£belonging,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£respect,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£fairness,ΓÇ¥ or ΓÇ£inclusive experiencesΓÇ¥ framings (CNBC, 2025; HRGrapevine, 2025; Marketplace, 2026). Consistent with this pattern, Paradigm reports a 22% decrease in Fortune 100 references to ΓÇ£DEI/diversityΓÇ¥ between 2023 and 2024 alongside a 59% increase in references to ΓÇ£belongingΓÇ¥ (Paradigm, 2025).Together, Incorporating these developments also helped us sharpen why the paperΓÇÖs central question remains important in the current climate. The paperΓÇÖs contribution is not simply that descriptive feedback may serve as a useful managerial tool, but that descriptive feedback about past selection patterns can change subsequent decisions when those patterns raise concerns about appearing prejudiced or failing to live up to your own egalitarian standards. The recent pullback from explicit DEI rhetoric in U.S. organizations is therefore relevant to the scope of our theory. To the extent that corporate messaging and formal diversity commitments are one source of peopleΓÇÖs motivation to respond without prejudice, their retreat may weaken that pathway. At the same time, these organizational cues are not the only source of such concerns. Anti-discrimination law, international transparency requirements, employee and stakeholder expectations, and individualsΓÇÖ own egalitarian commitments can continue to make race and gender consequential dimensions of evaluation, even when organizations no longer foreground DEI language. Thus, the current landscape does not simply make the paper less timely; it helps clarify when descriptive feedback should be more or less likely to matter. We now explain that descriptive feedback should be most influential when past selection patterns raise active concerns about prejudice, and less influential in contexts where those concerns are absent, muted, or explicitly rejected. Practically, this also reinforces the relevance of studying descriptive feedback as a light-touch approach: in settings where organizations are reluctant to issue explicit diversity goals, it remains important to understand whether making past selection patterns visible can still shape who is subsequently selected, hired, promoted, platformed, or featured.
