[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v1.md:85:> We have revised the Introduction (pp. X) and General Discussion to situate the paper within the current sociopolitical landscape around DEI, in response to Reviewer 2's concern that the prior version read as preΓÇæ2024. We acknowledge the recent U.S. retreat from explicit DEI rhetoric while documenting three countervailing patterns that reinforce the contemporary relevance of our research question. First, international regulatory demand for transparency around demographic representation continues to expand: Australia's Workplace Gender Equality Amendment (Closing the Gender Pay Gap) Act 2023 mandates public reporting of firmΓÇælevel gender representation and payΓÇægap data (Ressia, 2024); the EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970 requires memberΓÇæstate transposition by June 2026 (Mignano, 2024); and the EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381 establishes a 40% representation objective for the underrepresented gender on listedΓÇæcompany boards. Second, within the U.S., public and stakeholder sentiment has shifted more slowly than corporate rhetoric, with a 2025 Bentley/Gallup survey reporting that 69% of U.S. adults believe businesses should promote DEI (Bentley/Gallup, 2025), and antiΓÇæDEI shareholder proposals failing at numerous prominent organizations including Costco, Apple, Levi's, John Deere, and Goldman Sachs (CBS, 2025; Marketplace, 2025). Third, many firms appear to have rebranded their diversityΓÇærelated work, migrating toward "belonging," "inclusive culture," "respect," and "fairness" framings rather than dismantling it entirely (CNBC, 2025; HRGrapevine, 2025; Paradigm, 2025). Together, these developments helped us sharpen why our central question remains important: descriptive feedback about past selection patterns can change subsequent decisions when those patterns raise concerns about appearing prejudiced or failing to live up to one's own egalitarian standards, and these concerns persist even where corporate DEI language has receded.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v1.md:87:> We have provided a more tightly bounded theoretical discussion of the scope of our intervention, in line with Reviewer 2's request. We agree that motivation to respond without prejudice is central to our account, and we now distinguish two pathways through which descriptive feedback can shift selection decisions. The external motivation pathway is sustained not only by a firm's own DEI commitments but also by the fact that selection decisions are typically observable to colleagues, candidates, supervisors, and other stakeholders, and by an implicit injunctive norm against prejudicial behavior that is anchored in antiΓÇædiscrimination law, employee and customer scrutiny, and broader reputational concerns. A given firm's retreat from DEI rhetoric therefore reflects shifting external pressure on the firm, not the disappearance of broader social pressure on individual selection decisions (Levi & Fried, 2024). The internal motivation pathway, by contrast, is rooted in selectors' personally held egalitarian selfΓÇæimage and should be relatively insensitive to organizational climate; it is also the pathway most directly supported by Study 4's privateΓÇæfeedback paradigm and mediation evidence. We expect our effect to generalize wherever selections are observable and selectors hold at least some egalitarian commitments, and to be attenuated in fully private or anonymous selection contexts and in organizational settings that explicitly disavow egalitarian norms. We now flag organizational DEI climate as a scope condition and direction for future research in the General Discussion's Future Directions and Limitations section, alongside our existing discussions of public versus private feedback delivery, attribute visibility and implicit injunctive norms, and additional plausible mechanisms (e.g., fairness norms surfaced in Study 5's mechanism analysis) that descriptive feedback may also activate.
