[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_session.log:211:[codex] We have updated the references Reviewer 1 flagged as dated. Our introduction now provides more contemporary citations (e.g., to Locke and Latham (2019), Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018), Andor, Gerster, and Peters (2020), Henry, Ferraro, and Kontoleon (2019), and Mertens and Schultz (2021)); the General Discussion does the same, incorporating more recent work alongside the foundational citations we retain (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al., 2007)
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_session.log:213:[codex] We have revised the Introduction (pp. X) and Discussion to acknowledge the shifting socio-political landscape around organizational commitments to DEI in the United States flagged by Reviewer 2. We situate our work within two parallel developments. In the U.S., explicit DEI rhetoric has retreated since 2024. In addition, international governments have moved in the opposite direction, passing laws that require firms to disclose or correct gender disparities in pay and leadership. Australia's Workplace Gender Equality Amendment (Closing the Gender Pay Gap) Act of 2023 mandates public disclosure of firm-level gender representation and pay gaps (Ressia, 2024). The EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970 requires transposition across member states by June 2026 (Mignano, 2024). The EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381 establishes a 40% gender minimum on listed-company boards. We argue that these shifts reinforce the contemporary value of our research even against an ever-changing sociopolitical backdrop, with a recent decline in support for corporate diversity policies specifically in the United States.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_session.log:214:[codex] We have provided a more tightly bounded theoretical discussion of the scope of our intervention, in line with Reviewer 2╬ô├ç├ûs request. We agree that motivation to respond without prejudice is central to our account of increasing selections of women and racial minorities. However, we also discuss how the organizational climate around DEI is merely one part of the external motivation to control prejudice pathway that can influence individuals when it comes to promoting women and racial minorities. Specifically, the external motivation to control prejudice pathway also encompasses the fact that selection decisions are generally observable by colleagues, prospective candidates, and outside stakeholders, and the implicit norm against appearing prejudiced operates well beyond any one firm╬ô├ç├ûs stated commitments. While organizations╬ô├ç├û explicit DEI commitments are themselves often responses to external stakeholder, legal, and political pressures rather than the source of internal organizational norms (Levi & Fried, 2024), a given firm╬ô├ç├ûs retreat from DEI rhetoric reflects shifting external pressure on the firm, not the disappearance of broader social pressure on individual selection decisions. We also now discuss how the internal motivation to respond without prejudice as well as selectors╬ô├ç├û personally-held egalitarian beliefs may not be as malleable in the face of changes in organizational climate, and our existing evidence for why people respond to feedback about the race and gender of their past selectees (see Study 4) is, if anything, more readily explained by internal rather than external motives. In summary, we expect our effect to generalize wherever selections are observable and selectors hold at least some egalitarian commitments, and to be somewhat attenuated in fully private/anonymous selection decisions or in contexts that explicitly encourage discriminatory behavior.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_session.log:255:[codex] For the point about explicit goals being necessarily you cite some older stuff (e.g., Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al.,2007), any updated cites you can chuck in? Just makes it clearer how this is fitting in with contemporary literature in this area given that this is the first implication you discuss and the bigger one, I╬ô├ç├ûd like to see a bit more there.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_session.log:256:[codex] RESPONSE: Thank you for this helpful suggestion. We have updated our citations so we now cite Locke and Latham (2019) alongside the classic XX as well as Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018) alongside the classic XXX. These new citations reference contemporary updates to two foundational pieces we previously cited.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_session.log:258:[codex] RESPONSE: Thank you for pressing us on this point. We have refreshed the introduction╬ô├ç├ûs feedback and goals citations to draw on more recent work, including Locke and Latham (2019), Itzchakov and Latham (2018), Chen, Latham, and Piccolo (2020), Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018), and Devine and Ash (2022); and we have added applied work that the reviewer╬ô├ç├ûs prior comment first prompted us to incorporate (Andor, Gerster, & Peters, 2020; Henry, Ferraro, & Kontoleon, 2019; Mertens & Schultz, 2021).
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_session.log:259:[codex] More importantly, we have also expanded the theoretical framing (pp. X-X) to discuss how the classical feedback literature establishes that pairing feedback with an explicit goal works, but consistent with the broader logic of this literature, feedback regulates behavior only when there is a standard against which past performance can be evaluated. Our argument is that descriptive feedback can also be effective in domains where a strong implicit standard is already entrenched, such that no explicit goal need be paired alongside it. More specifically, we discuss how feedback evoking the past treatment of women and racial minorities provides a clean test of this theory. We note that anti-discrimination law, social and reputational pressures to behave in ways that are not prejudicial, and selectors╬ô├ç├û personally held egalitarian self-image jointly sustain an entrenched injunctive norm against prejudiced selection (Plant & Devine, 1998; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; Γö£├╝lvarez-Benjumea, 2023). When descriptive feedback reveals a discrepancy between this implicit standard and past behavior, we theorize that a motivation to respond without prejudice is activated even in the absence of a specific external goal. 
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\codex_session.log:269:[codex] The revised manuscript now more thoroughly discusses the fluctuating corporate posture toward DEI over the past five years: a period in which many U.S. organizations first rapidly adopted pro-DEI rhetoric and commitments, and then many of those same organizations have since scaled back on those commitments under new political, legal, and reputational pressures. At the same time, we also acknowledge two countervailing patterns that have occurred in parallel. First, internationally, regulatory demand for transparency around demographic representation is expanding: Australia╬ô├ç├ûs Workplace Gender Equality Amendment (Closing the Gender Pay Gap) Act 2023 mandates public reporting of firm-level gender representation and pay-gap data (Ressia, 2024); the EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970 requires member-state transposition by June 2026 (Mignano, 2024); and the EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381 establishes a 40% representation objective for the underrepresented gender on listed-company boards. Second, within the U.S., public and investor sentiment has shifted more slowly than corporate rhetoric. A 2025 Bentley/Gallup survey reports that 69% of U.S. adults believe businesses should promote DEI (Bentley/Gallup, 2025), and anti-DEI shareholder proposals have failed at numerous prominent organizations including Costco , Apple, Levi╬ô├ç├ûs, John Deere, Goldman Sachs, and others (CBS, 2025; Marketplace, 2025).Together, these patterns help explain why many (though not all) U.S. firms have rebranded their diversity functions rather than dismantled them. For example, Constellation Brands now uses ╬ô├ç┬úInclusive Culture Team,╬ô├ç┬Ñ Kohl╬ô├ç├ûs has shifted to ╬ô├ç┬úChief Inclusion and Belonging Officer,╬ô├ç┬Ñ and Nationwide and UPS have migrated to ╬ô├ç┬úbelonging,╬ô├ç┬Ñ ╬ô├ç┬úrespect,╬ô├ç┬Ñ ╬ô├ç┬úfairness,╬ô├ç┬Ñ or ╬ô├ç┬úinclusive experiences╬ô├ç┬Ñ framings (CNBC, 2025; HRGrapevine, 2025; Marketplace, 2026). Paradigm reports a 22% decrease in Fortune 100 references to ╬ô├ç┬úDEI/diversity╬ô├ç┬Ñ between 2023 and 2024 alongside a 59% increase in references to ╬ô├ç┬úbelonging╬ô├ç┬Ñ (Paradigm, 2025).In summary, we now situate the research more thoughtfully against the current landscape, acknowledging the shifts that have unfolded while clarifying the contexts in which this work remains both important and necessary.
