[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v2_codex.md:37:> We have updated the references that Reviewer 1 flagged as dated. The Introduction and General Discussion now draw on more contemporary work in the feedback, goal-setting, and social norms literatures, including Locke and Latham (2019), Itzchakov and Latham (2018), Chen, Latham, and Piccolo (2020), Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018), Devine and Ash (2022), Andor, Gerster, and Peters (2020), Henry, Ferraro, and Kontoleon (2019), and Mertens and Schultz (2021), alongside the foundational citations we retain.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v2_codex.md:41:> We have revised the Introduction (p. X) and General Discussion to acknowledge the shifting sociopolitical landscape around organizational commitments to DEI in the United States, in response to Reviewer 2ΓÇÖs concern that the prior version read as pre-2024. We now describe the recent U.S. retreat from explicit DEI rhetoric while also discussing three countervailing patterns that help explain why the paperΓÇÖs central question remains relevant. First, international regulatory demand for transparency around demographic representation continues to expand, including AustraliaΓÇÖs Workplace Gender Equality Amendment (Closing the Gender Pay Gap) Act 2023, the EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970, and the EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381. Second, within the U.S., public and stakeholder sentiment has shifted more slowly than some corporate and legal rhetoric: a 2025 Bentley/Gallup survey reports that 69% of U.S. adults believe businesses should promote DEI, and anti-DEI shareholder proposals have failed at prominent organizations including Costco, Apple, LeviΓÇÖs, John Deere, Goldman Sachs, and others. Third, many firms appear to have reframed or rebranded diversity-related work rather than dismantling it entirely, moving toward language such as belonging, inclusive culture, respect, fairness, and inclusive experiences. Together, these developments helped us clarify that the recent pullback from explicit DEI rhetoric is relevant to the scope of our theory, but does not remove all of the legal, social, reputational, and self-image concerns that can make descriptive feedback about race and gender selection patterns consequential.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v2_codex.md:60:- Kept the cover letter at a higher level and moved detailed evidence, including the 69% Bentley/Gallup figure, the shareholder proposal examples, and the rebranding patterns, into the in-body summary where the DE is asking for the coordinated response to Reviewers 1 and 2.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v2_codex.md:65:- Corrected house-style issues from v1, including straight apostrophes in firm names such as LeviΓÇÖs, straight quotation marks around manuscript language, and dash punctuation. I also retained ΓÇ£implicitΓÇ¥ throughout and avoided the disallowed alternative term.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v2_codex.md:66:- Open question for JC: the current manuscript export provided to Codex does not appear to contain all contemporary citations named in the R2 response letter, including Itzchakov and Latham (2018), Chen, Latham, and Piccolo (2020), Devine and Ash (2022), Andor, Gerster, and Peters (2020), Henry, Ferraro, and Kontoleon (2019), Mertens and Schultz (2021), and Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018). If `manuscript_gdoc_text.txt` is current, the manuscript and response letter still need to be aligned before submission.
