[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v3.md:26:> We have modernized the references that anchor our theoretical framing in response to Reviewer 1's request for more contemporary citations. Both the Introduction and General Discussion now draw on more recent feedback, goalΓÇæsetting, and socialΓÇænorms work (e.g., Locke & Latham, 2019; Itzchakov & Latham, 2018; Chen, Latham, & Piccolo, 2020; Schultz, Nolan, & Cialdini, 2018; Devine & Ash, 2022; Andor, Gerster, & Peters, 2020; Henry, Ferraro, & Kontoleon, 2019; Mertens & Schultz, 2021), alongside the foundational citations we retain.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v3.md:30:> We have situated the paper in the current sociopolitical landscape around DEI, in response to Reviewer 2's concern that the prior version read as preΓÇæ2024. We now acknowledge the recent U.S. retreat from explicit DEI rhetoric while documenting three countervailing patterns that keep our central question relevant: (a) expanded international transparency requirements (Australia's Workplace Gender Equality Amendment Act 2023, the EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970, and the EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381); (b) continued U.S. public and stakeholder support for corporate DEI (e.g., the 2025 Bentley/Gallup survey reporting majority public support, and recent defeats of antiΓÇæDEI shareholder proposals at Costco, Apple, Levi's, John Deere, and Goldman Sachs); and (c) firmΓÇælevel rebranding of diversity work (toward "belonging," "inclusive culture," and related framings) rather than wholesale dismantling.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v3.md:54:> **RESPONSE:** We have addressed both of these. The Introduction and General Discussion now draw on more contemporary work in the feedback, goalΓÇæsetting, and socialΓÇænorms literatures (e.g., Locke & Latham, 2019; Itzchakov & Latham, 2018; Chen, Latham, & Piccolo, 2020; Schultz, Nolan, & Cialdini, 2018; Devine & Ash, 2022; Andor, Gerster, & Peters, 2020; Henry, Ferraro, & Kontoleon, 2019; Mertens & Schultz, 2021), alongside the foundational citations we retain (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al., 2007). We have also expanded the Introduction's theoretical framing (pp. XΓÇæX) to articulate why descriptive feedback alone can shift selection decisions about women and underrepresented minorities. Consistent with the broader logic of the feedback literature, feedback regulates behavior only when past performance can be evaluated against a standard; we now make explicit that this standard need not be supplied by an explicit goal when an implicit injunctive norm against prejudicial selection is already entrenched, as it is for the diversityΓÇærelated selection decisions we study. We address Reviewer 1's specific suggestions in detail below.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v3.md:58:> **RESPONSE:** We have addressed both points. The Introduction (pp. X) and General Discussion now situate the paper within the current sociopolitical landscape around DEI: we acknowledge the recent U.S. retreat from explicit DEI rhetoric while documenting three countervailing patterns that reinforce the contemporary relevance of our central question, namely expanded international transparency requirements (Australia's WGEA amendment 2023; the EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970; the EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381), continued U.S. public and stakeholder support for corporate DEI (Bentley/Gallup, 2025; defeated antiΓÇæDEI shareholder proposals at Costco, Apple, Levi's, John Deere, and Goldman Sachs), and firmΓÇælevel rebranding of diversity work toward "belonging" and "inclusive culture" framings rather than wholesale dismantling.
[codex] revision-analysis/_r2_review\cover_letter_drafts_v3.md:60:> On the theoretical positioning, we now distinguish two pathways through which descriptive feedback shifts selection decisions: an *external* motivation to respond without prejudice, sustained by antiΓÇædiscrimination law, the observability of selection decisions, and broader reputational pressures that operate well beyond any one firm's stated DEI commitments (Levi & Fried, 2024); and an *internal* motivation to respond without prejudice, rooted in selectors' personally held egalitarian selfΓÇæimage, which should be relatively insensitive to organizational climate and is the pathway most directly supported by Study 4's privateΓÇæfeedback paradigm and mediation evidence. We expect our effect to generalize wherever selections are observable and selectors hold at least some egalitarian commitments, and to attenuate in fully private or anonymous selection contexts and in organizational settings that explicitly disavow egalitarian norms. We now flag organizational DEI climate as a scope condition and direction for future research in the General Discussion's *Future Directions and Limitations* section.
