[codex] +> Consistent with the broader logic of the feedback literature, feedback regulates behavior only when there is a standard against which past performance can be evaluated. The classical literature establishes that pairing feedback with an explicit goal supplies that standard. But the same logic implies that descriptive feedback alone can be effective in domains where a strong implicit standard is already entrenched, such that no explicit goal need be paired alongside it. Diversity-related selection decisions provide a clean test of this argument because anti-discrimination law, social and reputational pressures to avoid appearing prejudiced, and selectorsΓÇÖ personally held egalitarian self-image jointly sustain an entrenched implicit injunctive norm against prejudiced selection (Plant & Devine, 1998; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; ├ülvarez-Benjumea, 2023). When descriptive feedback reveals a discrepancy between this implicit standard and past behavior, we theorize that motivation to respond without prejudice is activated even in the absence of a specific external goal.
[codex] +
[codex] +Why this wording: The paragraph tracks the response letterΓÇÖs theory commitment closely, especially the standard-setting logic and the diversity selection context as the clean test case. It also keeps the claim bounded to domains where the implicit injunctive norm is already entrenched.
[codex] +
[codex] +## Item 4
[codex] +Locator: New Study 1 Discussion paragraph after manuscript line 50 and before the Figure 3 placeholder.
[codex] +
[codex] +> To address the possibility that Study 1ΓÇÖs pattern was driven by participants viewing gender as more important than the comparison attributes, we conducted a separate pretest. We recruited N = 300 Prolific participants in a between-subjects design in which each participant rated one expert attribute on a 1 to 7 importance scale, with the NPR producer framing held constant. Participants rated whether a guest was a woman as moderately important (M = 3.64, SD = 1.76, n = 76). By comparison, participants rated ΓÇ£worked at a universityΓÇ¥ as more important (M = 4.67, SD = 1.60; t(148.8) = -3.76, p < .001, d = -0.61) and ΓÇ£were under 50 years oldΓÇ¥ as more important (M = 4.44, SD = 1.73; t(149.0) = -2.81, p = .006, d = -0.46), while ΓÇ£based on the West Coast of the United StatesΓÇ¥ did not differ significantly in importance (M = 3.37, SD = 1.75; t(149.0) = 0.95, p = .343, d = +0.16). These results make Study 1 a conservative test: the comparison attributes were rated as equally or more important than gender, so differences in perceived importance cannot explain why only gender feedback moved subsequent selections.
[codex] +
[codex] +Why this wording: The paragraph uses only the finalized response-letter values and frames the pretest as a conservative test. It directly addresses the reviewerΓÇÖs concern without implying that attribute importance is the paperΓÇÖs mechanism.
[codex] +
[codex] +## Item 5
[codex] +Locator: General Discussion line 170, sentence beginning ΓÇ£According to Feedback Intervention Theory...ΓÇ¥
[codex] +
[codex] +CURRENT text:
[codex] +
[codex] +> According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al., 2007).
[codex] +
[codex] +PROPOSED text:
[codex] +
[codex] +> According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Locke & Latham, 2019; Schultz et al., 2007; Schultz, Nolan, & Cialdini, 2018).
