[codex] +## Item 6
[codex] +Locator: New paragraph in Theoretical and Practical Contributions after manuscript line 170, immediately after the sentence ending ΓÇ£an implicit injunctive norm to avoid prejudice has already been internalized by the decision-maker.ΓÇ¥
[codex] +
[codex] +> Our account also distinguishes two pathways through which descriptive feedback can change selection decisions. The first is external motivation to control prejudice. This pathway is driven by the observability of selection decisions to colleagues, candidates, supervisors, customers, employees, and other stakeholders, as well as by legal accountability and reputational concerns. FirmsΓÇÖ public DEI rhetoric can amplify these pressures, but it is better understood as a downstream signal of a broader legal and social environment rather than the source of the implicit injunctive norm itself (Levi & Fried, 2024). The second is internal motivation to control prejudice, which reflects selectorsΓÇÖ personally held egalitarian beliefs and their desire to see themselves as non-prejudiced decision makers. This pathway is the one most directly supported by Study 4, where feedback was delivered privately and internal motivation to respond without prejudice was the dominant mediator of subsequent selections. Study 4BΓÇÖs political-ideology null is consistent with this account, suggesting that both external motivation to control prejudice and internal motivation to control prejudice may operate across the political spectrum.
[codex] +
[codex] +Why this wording: The paragraph separates the two pathways using the required terms while treating firmsΓÇÖ DEI rhetoric as a downstream signal, not the source of the norm. The final sentence supplies the requested bridge from the Study 4B ideology null to both pathways.
