[codex] +## Item 2
[codex] +Locator: Introduction line 10, sentence beginning ΓÇ£Similarly, Schultz et al. (2007) found...ΓÇ¥
[codex] +
[codex] +CURRENT text:
[codex] +
[codex] +> Similarly, Schultz et al. (2007) found that when households received feedback about their energy usage alongside an explicit injunctive norm communicating that conservation was desirable as well as a social comparison to the energy use of their neighbors, energy consumption dropped by 5.7%.
[codex] +
[codex] +PROPOSED text:
[codex] +
[codex] +> Similarly, Schultz et al. (2007) found that when households received feedback about their energy usage alongside an explicit injunctive norm communicating that conservation was desirable as well as a social comparison to the energy use of their neighbors, energy consumption dropped by 5.7%. Together, the original Schultz et al. (2007) study and the later reprise by Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018) illustrate the value of feedback designs that pair information about past behavior with a clear normative standard, a pattern echoed in more recent applied interventions in energy and household conservation domains (Andor, Gerster, & Peters, 2020; Henry, Ferraro, & Kontoleon, 2019; Mertens & Schultz, 2021).
[codex] +
[codex] +Why this wording: This follows the default append approach, preserving text already approved in the prior revision while adding the reprise and applied feedback citations. The added sentence keeps the theoretical point focused on feedback paired with normative information.
[codex] +
[codex] +## Item 3
[codex] +Locator: New Introduction paragraph immediately before manuscript line 17, the paragraph beginning ΓÇ£We propose that when descriptive feedback reveals...ΓÇ¥
[codex] +
[codex] +> Consistent with the broader logic of the feedback literature, feedback regulates behavior only when there is a standard against which past performance can be evaluated. The classical literature establishes that pairing feedback with an explicit goal supplies that standard. But the same logic implies that descriptive feedback alone can be effective in domains where a strong implicit standard is already entrenched, such that no explicit goal need be paired alongside it. Diversity-related selection decisions provide a clean test of this argument because anti-discrimination law, social and reputational pressures to avoid appearing prejudiced, and selectorsΓÇÖ personally held egalitarian self-image jointly sustain an entrenched implicit injunctive norm against prejudiced selection (Plant & Devine, 1998; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; ├ülvarez-Benjumea, 2023). When descriptive feedback reveals a discrepancy between this implicit standard and past behavior, we theorize that motivation to respond without prejudice is activated even in the absence of a specific external goal.
[codex] +
[codex] +Why this wording: The paragraph tracks the response letterΓÇÖs theory commitment closely, especially the standard-setting logic and the diversity selection context as the clean test case. It also keeps the claim bounded to domains where the implicit injunctive norm is already entrenched.
[codex] +
[codex] +## Item 4
[codex] +Locator: New Study 1 Discussion paragraph after manuscript line 50 and before the Figure 3 placeholder.
[codex] +
[codex] +> To address the possibility that Study 1ΓÇÖs pattern was driven by participants viewing gender as more important than the comparison attributes, we conducted a separate pretest. We recruited N = 300 Prolific participants in a between-subjects design in which each participant rated one expert attribute on a 1 to 7 importance scale, with the NPR producer framing held constant. Participants rated whether a guest was a woman as moderately important (M = 3.64, SD = 1.76, n = 76). By comparison, participants rated ΓÇ£worked at a universityΓÇ¥ as more important (M = 4.67, SD = 1.60; t(148.8) = -3.76, p < .001, d = -0.61) and ΓÇ£were under 50 years oldΓÇ¥ as more important (M = 4.44, SD = 1.73; t(149.0) = -2.81, p = .006, d = -0.46), while ΓÇ£based on the West Coast of the United StatesΓÇ¥ did not differ significantly in importance (M = 3.37, SD = 1.75; t(149.0) = 0.95, p = .343, d = +0.16). These results make Study 1 a conservative test: the comparison attributes were rated as equally or more important than gender, so differences in perceived importance cannot explain why only gender feedback moved subsequent selections.
[codex] +
[codex] +Why this wording: The paragraph uses only the finalized response-letter values and frames the pretest as a conservative test. It directly addresses the reviewerΓÇÖs concern without implying that attribute importance is the paperΓÇÖs mechanism.
[codex] +
[codex] +## Item 5
[codex] +Locator: General Discussion line 170, sentence beginning ΓÇ£According to Feedback Intervention Theory...ΓÇ¥
[codex] +
[codex] +CURRENT text:
[codex] +
[codex] +> According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al., 2007).
[codex] +
[codex] +PROPOSED text:
[codex] +
[codex] +> According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Locke & Latham, 2019; Schultz et al., 2007; Schultz, Nolan, & Cialdini, 2018).
[codex] +
[codex] +Why this wording: This is the precise citation-block replacement requested. It retains the established General Discussion claim while adding the contemporary goal-setting and social-norms updates promised to Reviewer 1.
[codex] +
[codex] +## Item 6
[codex] +Locator: New paragraph in Theoretical and Practical Contributions after manuscript line 170, immediately after the sentence ending ΓÇ£an implicit injunctive norm to avoid prejudice has already been internalized by the decision-maker.ΓÇ¥
[codex] +
[codex] +> Our account also distinguishes two pathways through which descriptive feedback can change selection decisions. The first is external motivation to control prejudice. This form of motivation is driven by the observability of selection decisions to colleagues, candidates, supervisors, customers, employees, and other stakeholders, as well as by legal accountability and reputational concerns. FirmsΓÇÖ public DEI rhetoric can amplify these pressures, but it is better understood as a downstream signal of a broader legal and social environment rather than the source of the implicit injunctive norm itself (Levi & Fried, 2024). The second is internal motivation to control prejudice, which reflects selectorsΓÇÖ personally held egalitarian beliefs and their desire to see themselves as non-prejudiced decision makers. This form of motivation is the one most directly supported by Study 4, where feedback was delivered privately and internal motivation to control prejudice was the dominant mediator of subsequent selections. Study 4BΓÇÖs political-ideology null is consistent with this account, suggesting that both external motivation to control prejudice and internal motivation to control prejudice may operate across the political spectrum.
[codex] +
[codex] +Why this wording: The paragraph separates the two pathways using the required terms while treating firmsΓÇÖ DEI rhetoric as a downstream signal, not the source of the norm. The final sentence supplies the requested bridge from the Study 4B ideology null to both pathways.
[codex] +
[codex] +## Item 7
[codex] +Locator: Study 4 Discussion line 132, paragraph beginning ΓÇ£In addition, Study 4B established...ΓÇ¥
[codex] +
[codex] +CURRENT text:
[codex] +
[codex] +> In addition, Study 4B established that the effect of gender feedback was not moderated by political ideology nor party affiliation. Finally, it ruled out the possibility that our effects were driven by perceptions of which attributes were considered most important.
[codex] +
[codex] +PROPOSED text:
[codex] +
[codex] +> In addition, Study 4B established that the effect of gender feedback was not moderated by political ideology nor party affiliation. Finally, it ruled out the possibility that our effects were driven by perceptions of which attributes were considered most important. Although we are cautious about over-interpreting a null interaction, this pattern is suggestive that descriptive feedback operates across partisan lines. This interpretation converges with field-experiment evidence from Kirgios et al. (2022), who found that women and racial minorities benefited similarly from explicitly naming their demographic identity when seeking help from Republican and Democratic city counselors, an effect mediated by counselorsΓÇÖ motivation to control prejudice.
[codex] +
[codex] +Why this wording: The added text interprets the null conservatively and uses Kirgios et al. (2022) as corroborating field evidence rather than as proof of the null. The cross-spectrum bridge belongs at the end of Item 6, where it can connect the political-ideology result to both pathways.
[codex] +
[codex] +## Item 8
[codex] +Locator: Introduction line 15, replacement for the final sentence beginning ΓÇ£And despite recent rollbacks...ΓÇ¥
[codex] +
[codex] +> Over the past five years, the organizational context surrounding diversity, equity, and inclusion has shifted substantially. Following the racial justice protests of 2020, many U.S. organizations rapidly expanded public DEI commitments, representation goals, training programs, and diversity infrastructure (Devine & Ash, 2022; Ellis, 2025). By 2024 and 2025, however, some firms had scaled back explicit DEI goals, staffing, and language in response to new legal, political, and reputational pressures in the United States (Heaton, 2025). This changed landscape matters for our theory because explicit organizational commitments are one source of pressure on evaluators. Yet it does not eliminate the central question of whether making past selection patterns visible can change subsequent decisions.
[codex] +>
[codex] +> Three countervailing patterns suggest that this question remains consequential. First, regulatory demand for transparency around demographic representation has continued to expand outside the United States. AustraliaΓÇÖs Workplace Gender Equality Amendment (Closing the Gender Pay Gap) Act 2023 strengthened public reporting of firm-level gender representation and pay-gap data (Ressia, 2024), the EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970 requires member-state transposition by June 2026 (Mignano, 2024), and the EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381 establishes a 40% representation objective for the underrepresented gender on listed-company boards. Second, U.S. public and stakeholder support has shifted more slowly than corporate rhetoric. A 2025 Bentley University and Gallup survey found that 69% of U.S. adults believe businesses should promote DEI (Bentley University & Gallup, 2025), and recent anti-DEI shareholder proposals have failed at prominent firms including Costco, Apple, LeviΓÇÖs, John Deere, Goldman Sachs, and others (CBS News, 2025; Marketplace, 2025). Third, many firms appear to be reframing diversity-related work rather than abandoning it entirely. For example, Constellation Brands has used the label ΓÇ£Inclusive Culture Team,ΓÇ¥ KohlΓÇÖs has shifted to ΓÇ£Chief Inclusion and Belonging Officer,ΓÇ¥ and Nationwide and UPS have emphasized language such as ΓÇ£belonging,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£respect,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£fairness,ΓÇ¥ and ΓÇ£inclusive experiencesΓÇ¥ (Elias & Palmer, 2025; Dungan, 2025; Marketplace, 2026). Consistent with this pattern, Paradigm reports a 22% decrease in Fortune 100 references to ΓÇ£DEI/diversityΓÇ¥ between 2023 and 2024 alongside a 59% increase in references to ΓÇ£belongingΓÇ¥ (Paradigm, 2025).
[codex] +>
[codex] +> These developments sharpen, rather than weaken, the paperΓÇÖs theoretical contribution. Our claim is not that descriptive feedback is a managerial tool firms can deploy with equal force in any climate. Rather, we theorize and test whether descriptive feedback about past selection patterns can change subsequent decisions when those patterns raise concerns about appearing prejudiced or failing to live up to oneΓÇÖs own egalitarian standards. The current DEI landscape therefore helps clarify the scope of the effect: descriptive feedback should be most consequential where race and gender remain salient dimensions of evaluation because of law, transparency requirements, stakeholder scrutiny, organizational norms, or evaluatorsΓÇÖ own egalitarian self-image.
[codex] +
[codex] +Why this wording: The replacement expands the single dated sentence into a bounded, current landscape paragraph while avoiding a defensive response-letter tone. It also places Devine & Ash (2022) near the IntroductionΓÇÖs normative-context discussion, where it can support the broader organizational diversity-training backdrop.
[codex] +
[codex] +## Item 9
[codex] +Locator: New Introduction clarification after manuscript line 17 and before ΓÇ£Summary of the Current Research.ΓÇ¥
[codex] +
[codex] +> This prediction does not require assuming that participantsΓÇÖ initial selections reflect an appropriate or normative benchmark for any attribute. Instead, we predict that descriptive feedback shifts subsequent selections only when the attribute summarized by the feedback carries an implicit injunctive norm that the feedback calls into question. Gender and race are such dimensions in our studies because low representation of women or racial minorities can raise concerns about prejudiced selection. The comparison attributes we test, including whether candidates worked at a university, were under 50, were based on the West Coast, wrote in multiple genres, or possessed other task-relevant characteristics, may be more or less desirable in a given setting, but they do not carry the same implicit injunctive norm.
[codex] +
[codex] +Why this wording: This paragraph makes the no-appropriate-level clarification in the theoretical section rather than burying it in a study-specific note. It preserves the central contrast between gender and race feedback and the comparison attributes without implying any correct baseline.
[codex] +
[codex] +## Item 10
[codex] +Locator: Study 4 Discussion footnote attached to manuscript line 132 or the local sentence about attribute importance.
[codex] +
[codex] +> We do not assume that participantsΓÇÖ initial selections reflected an appropriate level of representation for the comparison attributes in Study 4, nor do we assume that there is a correct base rate for any attribute in the absence of an explicit goal or prescription. We interpret the effect of gender and racial feedback in this paradigm as evidence that those dimensions carry an implicit injunctive norm that the feedback calls into question, not as evidence that participants under-selected women or racial minorities relative to an objectively correct base rate.
[codex] +
[codex] +Why this wording: The footnote mirrors Item 9 in the local Study 4 context and makes clear that the interpretation rests on implicit injunctive norms, not on a hidden benchmark. It avoids the out-of-scope Table R1 pooled analysis.
[codex] +
[codex] +## Item 11
[codex] +Locator: Future Directions and Limitations, new paragraph after manuscript line 176.
[codex] +
[codex] +> Organizational DEI climate is another important scope condition. Descriptive feedback should be most likely to change subsequent selections when the organizational setting makes past selection patterns consequential for evaluatorsΓÇÖ reputations, legal accountability, stakeholder relationships, or self-image as egalitarian decision makers. It should matter less in settings where selections are fully private, where demographic patterns are unlikely to be seen as evidence of prejudice, or where an organization openly rejects egalitarian norms. Recent shifts in U.S. DEI rhetoric therefore do not make the intervention categorically irrelevant; instead, they clarify that its effect should depend on whether race and gender remain dimensions on which evaluators anticipate external scrutiny or experience internal pressure to act consistently with egalitarian commitments.
[codex] +
[codex] +Why this wording: I place this in Future Directions and Limitations because line 176 already discusses private versus public feedback and the relative role of external motivation. The passage ties the IntroductionΓÇÖs DEI landscape to the theory by making organizational climate a scope condition rather than a background trend.
[codex] +
[codex] +## Item 12
[codex] +Locator: Future Directions and Limitations, after the manuscript line 175 sentence ending ΓÇ£though this threshold is likely context dependent.ΓÇ¥
[codex] +
[codex] +> More broadly, motivation to respond without prejudice is unlikely to be the only mechanism through which descriptive feedback affects selection. Descriptive feedback can also make fairness norms and broader concerns about appropriate representation salient. Study 5 provides initial evidence for this possibility: when women were overrepresented in initial selections, fairness concerns led participants to select more men, thereby reducing gender imbalance. Future research could examine when descriptive feedback primarily activates prejudice concerns, when it activates fairness concerns, and when these motives jointly shape subsequent selections.
[codex] +
[codex] +Why this wording: This passage generalizes from Study 5ΓÇÖs mechanism analysis without overstating fairness as the main mechanism in the underrepresentation studies. It also fits the surrounding Future Directions discussion of thresholds and context dependence.
